arn again???</span><hr size=1> ok  im 100% japanese and japanese was my first language cuz dats all my parents spoke fluently and we live in da us.  and ive been going to japanese school since i started school and about 9 and now dat im 14 i have a hard time reading (even though i could read hiragana and katakana but not as fluent as before...and the simple kanji)   well now i have a whole summer to do nothing and i wanted to start studying and reading japanese books and i know its hard but im willing to try...and i some opinion on weather i should <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rakuraku>Rakuraku</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/18/03 9:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1137.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Should i learn again???</span><hr size=1>  I've been in a similar situation as you, and believe me you should spend as much time as possible to learn while you still have lots of free time (you will deeply regret it later if you don't).<br>
<br>
 PS: Even if you are on the internet you should make the effort to properly write in English as well. When you get lazy in English, it's too easy to get lazy in Japanese too. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nycborn919>NYCborn919</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/18/03 11:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1137.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Should i learn again???</span><hr size=1> Thanks for the reply...my parents always told me that I will regret it if I forget all the japanese that I spent a whole lot of time learning, I just had to hear it from someone else.  So, are you Japanese or what? and How long did it take you to learn this stuff?<br>
<br>
   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rakuraku>Rakuraku</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/18/03 9:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1137.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Should i learn again???</span><hr size=1>  My mother is Japanese, but I've lived all my life in Canada. I attended a Japanese saturday school for 12 years, but have made little progress compared to my younger days. I'm pretty much stuck to about the level of a 4th grader in Japan.<br>
 And yes, it is very easy to forget everything. It is unfortunate that Japanese has such a difficult writing system, which makes it much harder to retain fluency. I know many people from my school who had both parents Japanese and yet they could barely say much beyond 'hello' and 'thank you'. Some of these people could care less, but some of them feel very bad because they now want to visit Japan and can't even communicate with their relatives!<br>
 Now I am busy with the responsibilities of an adult: work, taxes, etc. It is a challenge for me to remember what I know now, let alone learn new things. I do make an effort to read/write Japanese at least once a week (and of course I always speak in Japanese with my mother).<br>
  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maimaipanda>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Resident Panda</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/19/03 7:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1137.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/temp/pandatea.jpg height=146 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Should i learn again???</span><hr size=1> &gt; Now I am busy with the responsibilities of an adult: work, taxes<br>
<br>
hmm, you know, i never really considered 'taxes' as an area of my life where i spend significant amounts of time.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   they pretty much just take it from me without my say!<br>
<br>
anyway, i have to second what raku said.  having only studied japanese in college, i have to admit to a great deal of jealousy at the kids who grew up in japanese-english bilingual households/ chinese students who could already write kanji, etc.<br>
<br>
i can think of no godly reason why you should not seek to leverage this natural advantage and seek to become fluent in both languages.  it can only help you in the future.<br>
<br>
best to study language while you're young - when you get to be a creaking panda in your 20's like me, it'll take a whole lot more misery to pound new things into your head.   <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;">Mamonaku. 11ban sen ni  Panda densha ga mairimasu. </span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;">Abunai desu kara, kiiro no sen no uchigawa made osagarikudasai.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->  </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
